{:proof/problem-id "apm-aunk01", :proof/classification :partial, :proof/output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ · notes: Statement explicitly references Borel sets, Lebesgue measure, and L¹ integrals under translation, matching parts (a)-(c).\n\n```\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Prove that translations preserve Borel structure, Lebesgue measure, and L¹ integrals on ℝ.\"\n :terms [{:name \"translation map\"\n          :meaning \"τ_y(x)=x+y is a homeomorphism of ℝ\"\n          :needed-because \"Homeomorphisms send Borel sets to Borel sets and preserve measurability of integrands.\"}\n         {:name \"translation invariance of Lebesgue measure\"\n          :meaning \"m(A+y)=m(A) for every measurable A and y\"\n          :needed-because \"This yields the measure identity and underlies the change-of-variables step.\"}\n         {:name \"change of variables\"\n          :meaning \"∫ f(x+y) dm(x) = ∫ f(u) dm(u) via u=x+y\"\n          :needed-because \"Converts the integrand back to f itself, proving invariance.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"translation_map_measurable\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Use that τ_y is continuous and invertible\"\n             :why-this-now \"Establish that A+y remains Borel because τ_y^{-1}(A+y)=A.\"\n             :lean-target \"borel_map_translation\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Continuous additive maps are measurable; translation homeomorphisms already live in Mathlib.\"}\n            {:id :s2\n             :formal-dependency \"measure_preserving_translation\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Known theorem: Lebesgue measure is invariant under translations\"\n             :why-this-now \"Directly gives m(A+y)=m(A).\"\n             :lean-target \"Real.volume_preimage_add_eq\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Translation invariance for Haar measure on ℝ is in Mathlib.\"}\n            {:id :s3\n             :formal-dependency \"integral_comp_translation\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Apply change of variables using the measure-preserving map\"\n             :why-this-now \"Shows the L¹ integral is unchanged.\"\n             :lean-target \"integral_comp_add_right\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Exists as `MeasureTheory.integral_add_right_eq_self`.\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"Translations of ℝ are Borel-measurable, measure-preserving, and keep L¹ integrals unchanged.\"\n             :formal-name \"translation_preserves_measure_and_integral\"\n             :formal-target \"∀ (y : ℝ) (A : Set ℝ) (f : ℝ → ℝ),\n    MeasurableSet A ∧ Integrable f →\n    MeasurableSet ((fun x => x + y) '' A) ∧\n    volume ((fun x => x + y) '' A) = volume A ∧\n    (∫ x, f (x + y) = ∫ x, f x)\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"Bundles parts (a)-(c) into a single Lean statement about translation invariance.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"translation_preserves_measure_and_integral\"\n              :formal-statement \"same as formal-target\"\n              :informal-clause \"Collects the statements from parts (a)-(c).\"\n              :role :main-theorem}\n             {:formal-name \"measure_preserving_add_right\"\n              :formal-statement \"∀ y : ℝ, MeasurePreserving fun x => x + y\"\n              :informal-clause \"Used to deduce both the set-measure fact and the integral equality.\"\n              :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Why it’s hard.**  \nPart (a) tempts you to take images of Borel sets, but measurable images need not remain Borel unless you notice that translation is a homeomorphism and work with preimages instead.  For (b) many students try to deduce \\(m(A+y)=m(A)\\) by plugging the indicator of \\(A\\) into (c); that fails when \\(m(A)=\\infty\\), so you really need the general theorem that Lebesgue measure is the Haar measure on \\((\\mathbb R,+)\\) and is translation invariant.  For (c) you must justify the substitution \\(u=x+y\\) inside the Lebesgue integral: it is not the Riemann-substitution trick but an instance of the change-of-variables formula for a measure-preserving bijection.\n\n**The key insight.**  \nPackage everything into the translation homeomorphism \\(\\tau_y(x)=x+y\\).  Homeomorphisms preserve the Borel \\(\\sigma\\)-algebra under preimages, Lebesgue measure is translation invariant (unique Haar measure), and a measure-preserving bijection leaves \\(L^1\\) integrals unchanged.  Once those facts are stated, all three parts follow immediately.\n\n**Complete proof.**  \nFix \\(y\\in\\mathbb R\\) and write \\(\\tau_y(x)=x+y\\).\n\n(a) \\(A+y=\\{z:z-y\\in A\\}=\\tau_{-y}^{-1}(A)\\).  Because \\(\\tau_{-y}\\) is continuous, the preimage of a Borel set is Borel, so \\(A+y\\) is Borel.\n\n(b) Lebesgue measure \\(m\\) is translation invariant: for every Borel \\(B\\), \\(m(\\tau_y^{-1}(B))=m(B)\\).  Apply this to \\(B=A+y\\) and use \\(\\tau_y^{-1}(A+y)=A\\) to conclude \\(m(A+y)=m(A)\\) (no finiteness assumption).\n\n(c) Let \\(f\\in L^{1}(\\mathbb R)\\).  Since \\(\\tau_y\\) is measure preserving, the change-of-variables formula gives\n\\[\n\\int_{\\mathbb R} f(x+y)\\,dm(x)\n=\\int_{\\mathbb R} f(\\tau_y x)\\,dm(x)\n=\\int_{\\mathbb R} f(x)\\,dm(x).\n\\]\nThat is exactly the desired identity.\n\n**Lean 4 formalization.**  \nThe intended Lean theorem is `translation_preserves_measure_and_integral`, bundling (a)–(c).  The plan is:\n\n1. Define `τ_y : x ↦ x + y` once and note `(fun x ↦ x - y)` is continuous, so `(fun x ↦ x - y) ⁻¹' A` is Borel, giving part (a).\n2. Use the Mathlib lemma asserting `MeasurePreserving (fun x ↦ x + y)` for `Real.volume`—this is Lebesgue’s translation invariance—to deduce part (b).\n3. Apply `MeasurePreserving.integral_comp` (a change-of-variables lemma) to prove part (c).\n\nI have documented this plan in the formal artifacts, but I was blocked in Stage 3 because I could not, within this environment, locate the exact Mathlib lemma names for translation invariance, so `Main.lean` is still empty and `lake build` has not yet been run.  Once those lemmas are located (they live in the Haar-measure infrastructure), wiring them in will mirror the informal proof verbatim.\n\n**What connects.**  \nEverything here is an instance of a general philosophy: for locally compact groups, Haar measure is invariant under group operations, and change of variables for a measure-preserving map gives integral invariance.  These ideas reappear in convolution definitions, the proof of Plancherel’s theorem, ergodic theory (since translations on the torus are measure preserving), and any exam question that asks you to justify “obvious” substitutions in Lebesgue integrals.", :proof/extraction {:phases {}, :dependency-graph nil, :arse-questions nil, :classification :partial, :phase-count 0, :dep-graph-count 0, :arse-count 0}, :proof/frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/Aunk01/Apm_v2_aunk01_1775005703226", :frame/id "apm-v2-aunk01-1775005703226", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :workspace/generated-at "2026-04-01T01:08:23.269362Z", :frame/shared-extension-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Local", :frame/module-root "ApmCanaries.Frames.Aunk01.Apm_v2_aunk01_1775005703226", :proof/problem-id "aunk01", :workspace/schema "proof-frame-workspace.v1", :frame/workspace-root "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/aunk01/apm-v2-aunk01-1775005703226", :artifacts {:proof-plan "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/aunk01/apm-v2-aunk01-1775005703226/proof-plan.edn", :formal-alignment "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/aunk01/apm-v2-aunk01-1775005703226/formal-alignment.edn", :changelog "/home/joe/code/futon